      <h1>Understanding M12 Connector Coding: A, B, D, X-Code Explained</h1>

      <p>M12 connectors are everywhere in industrial automation — sensors, actuators, fieldbus networks, and industrial Ethernet. But with multiple coding types (A, B, C, D, X, S, T), it is easy to order the wrong one.</p>

      <p>This guide explains each coding type and when to use it.</p>

      <h2>What Does "Coding" Mean?</h2>
      <p>M12 connectors use a <strong>coded keying system</strong> — a physical notch on the connector that prevents you from mating incompatible connectors together. Think of it like USB-A vs USB-B: you cannot physically plug one into the other.</p>

      <p>The coding type determines:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Which applications the connector is designed for</li>
        <li>How many pins it supports</li>
        <li>What speed/data protocol it carries</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The Main Coding Types</h2>

      <h3>A-Code: The General Purpose Connector</h3>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Pins</strong></td><td>3, 4, 5, 8, 12</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Speed</strong></td><td>Up to 100 Mbps</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Use</strong></td><td>Sensors, actuators, DC power</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>IP Rating</strong></td><td>IP67 / IP68</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p><strong>A-code</strong> is the most common M12 connector. If you are connecting a proximity sensor, photoelectric sensor, or simple actuator, this is what you need.</p>

      <h3>B-Code: For PROFIBUS</h3>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Pins</strong></td><td>4, 5</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Speed</strong></td><td>Up to 12 Mbps</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Use</strong></td><td>PROFIBUS DP/PA</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p><strong>B-code</strong> is specifically designed for PROFIBUS fieldbus communication. If you are not using PROFIBUS, you will likely never need this.</p>

      <h3>D-Code: For Industrial Ethernet (100 Mbps)</h3>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Pins</strong></td><td>4</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Speed</strong></td><td>100 Mbps (Cat5e)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Use</strong></td><td>PROFINET, EtherCAT, Modbus TCP</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>IP Rating</strong></td><td>IP67</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p><strong>D-code</strong> is the standard for 100 Mbps industrial Ethernet. If your robot or machine uses PROFINET or EtherCAT, you need D-code connectors.</p>

      <h3>X-Code: For Gigabit Ethernet (10 Gbps)</h3>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Pins</strong></td><td>8</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Speed</strong></td><td>10 Gbps (Cat6a)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Use</strong></td><td>Gigabit Ethernet, high-speed data</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>IP Rating</strong></td><td>IP67 / IP68</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p><strong>X-code</strong> is the premium choice for high-speed Ethernet. It uses individually shielded twisted pairs (SFTP) to achieve 10 Gbps. For robotics vision systems or industrial IoT applications requiring high bandwidth, X-code is the right choice.</p>

      <h2>Quick Selection Guide</h2>

      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Your Application</th><th>Use This Code</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Proximity / photoelectric sensor</td><td><strong>A-code</strong> (3 or 4 pin)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Actuator / solenoid valve</td><td><strong>A-code</strong> (4 or 5 pin)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>PROFIBUS network</td><td><strong>B-code</strong> (4 or 5 pin)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>PROFINET / EtherCAT (100M)</td><td><strong>D-code</strong> (4 pin)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Gigabit Ethernet (1G/10G)</td><td><strong>X-code</strong> (8 pin)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Power (AC, high current)</td><td><strong>S-code</strong> (3 or 4 pin)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Power (DC, high current)</td><td><strong>T-code</strong> (4 or 5 pin)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>Pin Number Matters Too</h2>
      <p>Even within the same coding type, the number of pins matters. A 4-pin A-code connector will not mate with a 5-pin A-code connector (the keying is the same, but the pins do not align).</p>

      <p>Common pin configurations:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>3-pin</strong>: DC sensors (PNP/NPN + GND)</li>
        <li><strong>4-pin</strong>: DC sensors with I/O, or Ethernet (D-code)</li>
        <li><strong>5-pin</strong>: Analog signals, IO-Link</li>
        <li><strong>8-pin</strong>: Gigabit Ethernet (X-code), or combined power+signal</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Mating Compatibility</h2>
      <p><strong>Different coding types cannot mate.</strong> This is intentional — it prevents expensive mistakes in industrial installations.</p>

